@page "/features"
@layout PublicLayout

<PageTitle>Features — Nornis</PageTitle>

<section class="nornis-landing-hero">
    <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Features</div>
    <h1 class="nornis-landing-title">Everything Nornis<br />remembers for you.</h1>
    <p class="nornis-landing-sub">
        Nornis reads the raw material of your game and proposes structured knowledge — people,
        places, factions, storylines, and the facts that connect them. You decide what becomes
        canon. Here is the whole of what it does.
    </p>
</section>

@* ---------------------------------------------------------------- Capture -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Capture</div>
        <h2>Get it out of your head</h2>
        <p>
            However you took the note, Nornis will take it. Raw and unpolished is fine — that's
            the point.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-grid">
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Create" Size="Size.Small" /> Session &amp; prep notes</h3>
            <p>
                Write or paste into a rich editor. Tag which campaign the events happened in and
                when, set who can see it, and send it for extraction — or keep it as a draft.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Gesture" Size="Size.Small" /> Handwriting</h3>
            <p>
                Photograph or scan pages of handwritten notes and Nornis transcribes them, then
                extracts knowledge from the transcription. Up to 50 pages, in reading order.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Draw" Size="Size.Small" /> Ink canvas</h3>
            <p>
                Write by hand directly in Nornis on a full-screen canvas with pen, eraser, and
                undo. Every stroke autosaves and survives a refresh; one button sends the pages
                on for transcription.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Image" Size="Size.Small" /> Images</h3>
            <p>
                Attach images and Nornis reads them for lore — the people, places, and things in
                the picture — and merges what it sees with whatever you typed alongside.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.UploadFile" Size="Size.Small" /> Documents</h3>
            <p>
                Upload PDFs, text, and markdown. The text is pulled out, combined with your own
                notes, and read as one source. Files stay downloadable from the source page.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Map" Size="Size.Small" /> Maps</h3>
            <p>
                Upload a map image and Nornis reads the place names and their positions off it,
                proposing locations already pinned. The finished map browses with live pins.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.AddComment" Size="Size.Small" /> Add from anywhere</h3>
            <p>
                On any entry in the codex, type what you just learned. It becomes a real,
                traceable source and flows through the normal review — no silent edits.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Inventory2" Size="Size.Small" /> Store without extracting</h3>
            <p>
                Some material is reference, not canon. Turn extraction off and the source is kept
                as part of the record without proposing a single change.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Inbox" Size="Size.Small" /> The sources ledger</h3>
            <p>
                Every source you're allowed to see, filterable by campaign and status, with
                processing state advancing live. Re-run extraction any time — with a preview of
                exactly what that would replace.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

@* ----------------------------------------------------------------- Record -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">The record</div>
        <h2>AI proposes. Your table decides.</h2>
        <p>
            Nothing enters accepted canon without a person saying yes — and everything that does
            keeps a link back to the sentence that produced it.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-grid">
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.AutoAwesome" Size="Size.Small" /> Extraction</h3>
            <p>
                Each source is read in the background and turned into proposals: entries to
                create or update, facts with truth states, relationships, storyline nesting, open
                questions, and map pins.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.FactCheck" Size="Size.Small" /> The review queue</h3>
            <p>
                Every proposal shows what it would change, how confident it is, which source it
                came from, and why. Accept it, edit the values first, or reject it — one at a
                time or all at once, in dependency-safe order.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.MenuBook" Size="Size.Small" /> The codex</h3>
            <p>
                Everything your world knows — characters, locations, items, factions, events,
                storylines, concepts, documents. Browse as cards, as a collapsible tree, or as a
                live force-directed graph.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Article" Size="Size.Small" /> Facts with texture</h3>
            <p>
                Not everything known is equally true. Each fact carries its state — confirmed,
                likely, rumor, disputed, false, or hidden — so a half-remembered tavern claim
                never reads like established history.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Hub" Size="Size.Small" /> Connections</h3>
            <p>
                Typed, described relationships between entries, with a mini-graph on every page
                you can widen from direct links to two hops out.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Source" Size="Size.Small" /> Provenance</h3>
            <p>
                Every entry lists the sources behind it, each with the quoted excerpt that
                supports it, linking straight back to the original note.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Search" Size="Size.Small" /> Search</h3>
            <p>
                Type-ahead search across the codex from the top bar of any page, with summaries
                on hover so you can tell two similar names apart before you click.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Merge" Size="Size.Small" /> Merge duplicates
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Imports produce name variants. Pick which one survives and the facts and
                relationships move across while the duplicate is archived — recorded as a
                reviewed change, not a quiet deletion.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Tune" Size="Size.Small" /> Curate
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Rename entries, move them between active, dormant, resolved, and archived, or
                remove them from canon — always with a preview of what goes with them.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

@* -------------------------------------------------------------- The table -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">At the table</div>
        <h2>The part you use mid-session</h2>
        <p>
            Answers in seconds, without remembering which note you wrote it in.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-grid">
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.QuestionAnswer" Size="Size.Small" /> Ask the Loremaster</h3>
            <p>
                Ask your world anything in plain language. Answers come only from your accepted
                record and your indexed library, every claim cited, with a confidence rating —
                and it tells you plainly when it doesn't know.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Shield" Size="Size.Small" /> Answers that respect the table</h3>
            <p>
                A player and a GM asking the same question get different answers, because what
                the Loremaster can retrieve depends on who is asking. Secrets stay secret.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Dashboard" Size="Size.Small" /> The dashboard</h3>
            <p>
                Active storylines, recent canon changes, what's waiting in review, and four
                questions worth asking — generated from the actual state of your world, not a
                static list.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Timeline" Size="Size.Small" /> Timeline</h3>
            <p>
                Storylines laid out over your real session calendar: what developed when, what's
                still open, what has gone quiet. Drag one arc onto another to nest it.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Route" Size="Size.Small" /> Journey map</h3>
            <p>
                The party's trail across the map, session by session. Drag the playhead and walk
                the route, surfacing what each stop meant as you go.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.HelpOutline" Size="Size.Small" /> Open questions</h3>
            <p>
                Unresolved tensions the record has noticed — kept visible on the entries and
                storylines they belong to, so a dangling thread doesn't quietly disappear.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.PlaylistAddCheck" Size="Size.Small" /> Session wrap-up
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                After a session lands, a card appears — and only when there's something to do.
                What advanced, what's gone quiet, what could nest, and which new arcs need a
                home. Each decision saves as you make it.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.MonitorHeart" Size="Size.Small" /> Continuity health
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                A read on how coherent your record is — contradictions, dangling threads, stale
                storylines, timeline conflicts — each finding with a severity, a suggested
                action, and a jump to the entry. The page shows its own arithmetic.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.History" Size="Size.Small" /> Retrospective
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Ask Nornis to read your active storylines against the record and propose closing
                the ones that clearly finished. The results arrive as ordinary proposals.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

@* --------------------------------------------------------------- Secrets -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Secrets</div>
        <h2>GM truth and player truth, kept apart</h2>
        <p>
            The hardest part of running a long game is remembering who knows what. Nornis tracks
            it for you.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-grid">
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.VisibilityOff" Size="Size.Small" /> Scope on everything</h3>
            <p>
                Every source, entry, fact, and connection is private, GM-only, or party-visible.
                Extraction never leaks GM-only material into party-visible knowledge, and the
                Loremaster won't quote what a player hasn't earned.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Visibility" Size="Size.Small" /> Reveal to the party
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                When the fiction gives a secret away, tick exactly what the party now learns and
                leave the rest hidden. Nornis checks the reveal leaves nothing dangling and tells
                you what else has to come with it.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Description" Size="Size.Small" /> Hand over the document
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Give the party the actual artifact — the map they bought, the letter they found —
                attachments and all. Revealing the map is a separate decision from revealing
                every place marked on it.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

@* --------------------------------------------------------------- Library -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Library</div>
        <h2>Your books, on the same shelf</h2>
        <p>
            Reference material lives beside your world's memory without ever becoming part of it.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-grid">
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.LibraryBooks" Size="Size.Small" /> Sourcebooks &amp; handouts</h3>
            <p>
                Upload the books, maps, and handouts your table actually uses. They're stored as
                reference — never extracted into canon.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.FormatQuote" Size="Size.Small" /> Quoted with page numbers</h3>
            <p>
                PDFs are indexed into passages, so "what happens at level 8?" comes back answered
                and cited to the page it came from.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.SwapHoriz" Size="Size.Small" /> Two shelves
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Keep the adventure module to yourself and the player's guide on the party shelf —
                and move a book between them whenever the campaign moves on.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

@* ------------------------------------------------------------ Your table -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Your table</div>
        <h2>Worlds that outlast campaigns</h2>
        <p>
            Knowledge belongs to the world. Campaigns record when it happened and who was there.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-grid">
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Public" Size="Size.Small" /> Worlds &amp; campaigns</h3>
            <p>
                One setting, many runs of play. The same NPCs and canon carry across the original
                campaign, the sequel years later, and the side game with a different party.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3><MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Groups" Size="Size.Small" /> Characters</h3>
            <p>
                Add your characters, link them to their entry in the codex, and claim one that's
                already there. Play several at once, or across several campaigns.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.PersonAdd" Size="Size.Small" /> Invite links
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Mint a link for a specific role, with an optional expiry and use limit. Revoke it
                whenever you like.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Share" Size="Size.Small" /> Share it publicly
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Give your world a public address and switch it on. Visitors get a read-only view
                of party-visible material only — the codex, the timeline, and session notes.
                Nothing hidden ever appears.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Payments" Size="Size.Small" /> Cost visibility
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Every AI call is metered by operation, model, and person, against a daily budget
                you set per world. No black boxes at your table.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="nornis-features-item">
            <h3>
                <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Outlined.Settings" Size="Size.Small" /> Run the world
                <span class="nornis-features-gm">GM</span>
            </h3>
            <p>
                Manage members and roles, edit campaigns and who played in them, and watch the
                processing queue — resubmitting anything that failed.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

@* ----------------------------------------------------------------- Roles -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Roles</div>
        <h2>Who sees what</h2>
        <p>
            Three roles, and they see genuinely different worlds.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-roles-scroll">
        <table class="nornis-features-roles">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th scope="col">Role</th>
                    <th scope="col">Can do</th>
                    <th scope="col">Cannot</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <th scope="row">GM</th>
                    <td>
                        Everything: capture, review every proposal, keep hidden canon, reveal it,
                        merge and curate entries, invite members, share the world, and run the
                        continuity tools.
                    </td>
                    <td>Un-reveal something. Reveals are one-way, on purpose.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th scope="row">Player</th>
                    <td>
                        Capture sources, read party-visible material, review the proposals their
                        own sources produced, ask the Loremaster, and manage their characters.
                    </td>
                    <td>See GM-only material, or author it.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th scope="row">Observer</th>
                    <td>Read party-visible material. A fly on the wall.</td>
                    <td>Capture, review, or change anything at all.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>
</section>

@* ---------------------------------------------------------------- Limits -- *@
<section class="nornis-features-section">
    <div class="nornis-features-head">
        <div class="nornis-eyebrow">Honest limits</div>
        <h2>What Nornis doesn't do</h2>
        <p>
            A tool that tells you what it can't do is easier to trust than one that doesn't.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="nornis-features-limits">
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>It doesn't listen to your session.</strong> There's no audio recording or
                transcription — paste a transcript you already have and Nornis will read that.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>It doesn't read the web for you.</strong> A link is stored beside your
                notes; Nornis doesn't fetch the page behind it.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>It doesn't un-reveal.</strong> Once the party knows, the record says they
                know. Reveals are deliberate and one-way.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>It doesn't reveal to one player.</strong> Reveals go to the whole party.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>It doesn't change canon on its own.</strong> Ever. Every change waits for
                a person.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>It isn't a virtual tabletop.</strong> No maps to fight on, no dice, no
                rules engine. Nornis is the memory beside the table, not the table.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="nornis-landing-final">
    <h2 class="nornis-landing-h2">Many sources feed one enduring epic.</h2>
    <p class="nornis-landing-sub">Start capturing tonight's session — Nornis will remember the rest.</p>
    <MudButton Variant="Variant.Filled" Color="Color.Secondary" Size="Size.Large" Href="/">
        Start your record
    </MudButton>
</section>
